'Andalusia' (, , , ; or ) is the most populous and the second largest in area of
the autonomous communities in Spain. The Andalusian autonomous community is
officially recognized as a [[nationalities and regions of Spain|nationality]] of
Spain. [http://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2007/03/20/pdfs/A11871-11909.pdf BoletÃ­n
Oficial del Estado of Spain, n. 68 of 2007/03/20, p. 11872.] Estatuto de
AutonomÃ­a de AndalucÃ­a. ArtÃ­culo 1: Â«AndalucÃ­a, como nacionalidad histÃ³rica y en
el ejercicio del derecho de autogobierno que reconoce la ConstituciÃ³n, se
constituye en Comunidad AutÃ³noma en el marco de la unidad de la naciÃ³n espaÃ±ola
y conforme al artÃ­culo 2 de la ConstituciÃ³n.Â» The territory is divided
into eight provinces: AlmerÃ­a, CÃ¡diz, CÃ³rdoba, Granada, Huelva, JaÃ©n, MÃ¡laga and
Seville. Its capital is the city of Seville (Spanish: Sevilla).

Andalusia is in the south of the Iberian peninsula, immediately south of the
autonomous communities of Extremadura and CastileâLa Mancha; west of the
autonomous community of Murcia and the Mediterranean Sea; east of Portugal and
the Atlantic Ocean; and north of the Mediterranean Sea and the Strait of
Gibraltar. The small British overseas territory of Gibraltar shares a three-quarter-
mile land border with the Andalusian province of CÃ¡diz at the eastern end of the
Strait of Gibraltar.

The main mountain ranges of Andalusia are the Sierra Morena and the Baetic
System, consisting of the Subbaetic and Penibaetic Mountains, separated by the
Intrabaetic Basin. In the north, the Sierra Morena separates Andalusia from the
plains of Extremadura and CastileâLa Mancha on Spain's Meseta Central. To the
south the geographic subregion of Upper Andalusia lies mostly within the Baetic
System, while Lower Andalusia is in the Baetic Depression of the valley of the
Guadalquivir. [http://aguas.igme.es/igme/publica/libro20/pdf/lib20/c_guadal-
_1.pdf Cuenca del Guadalquivir]

The name Andalusia traces back to the Arabic language [[Al-Andalus]] (Ø§ÙØ£ÙØ¯ÙØ³).
As well as Muslim and Romani influences, the region's history and culture have
been influenced by the earlier Iberians, Phoenicians, Carthaginians, Greeks,
Romans, Vandals, Visigoths, Byzantines, all of whom preceded the Muslims, as
well as the Castilian and other Christian North Iberian nationalities who
regained and repopulated the area in the latter phases of the [[Reconquista]].
There was also a relatively large Sephardic Jewish presence.

Andalusia has been an economically poor region in comparison with the rest of
Spain and the wider European Union. However, the growth of the community
especially in the sectors of industry and services was above average in Spain
and higher than many communities in the eurozone. The region has, however, a
rich culture and a strong cultural identity. Many cultural phenomena that are
seen internationally as distinctively Spanish are largely or entirely Andalusian
in origin. These include flamenco, bullfighting, and certain Moorish-influenced
architectural styles.
